{"award_age":41.0,"bio_image":"full\/2129d0a8bcbabe9cf5127fc4a1a30465365e186f.jpg","category":"Chemistry","country":"France","date_of_birth":"1871-05-06T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":"1935-12-13T00:00:00.000Z","gender":"male","image_urls":["http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/commons\/thumb\/c\/c4\/Viktor-grignard.jpg\/180px-Viktor-grignard.jpg"],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Victor_Grignard","mini_bio":"<p><b>Fran\u00e7ois Auguste Victor Grignard<\/b> (May 6, 1871 in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Cherbourg\" title=\"Cherbourg\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Cherbourg<\/a> - December 13, 1935 in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Lyon\" title=\"Lyon\">Lyon<\/a>) was a <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize\" title=\"Nobel Prize\">Nobel Prize<\/a>-winning French <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Chemist\" title=\"Chemist\">chemist<\/a>.<\/p><p>Grignard was the son of a sail maker. After studying mathematics at Lyon he transferred to chemistry and discovered the synthetic reaction bearing his name (the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Grignard_reaction\" title=\"Grignard reaction\">Grignard reaction<\/a>) in 1900. He became a professor at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_Nancy\" title=\"University of Nancy\" class=\"mw-redirect\">University of Nancy<\/a> in 1910 and was awarded the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Chemistry\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Chemistry\">Nobel Prize in Chemistry<\/a> in 1912. During <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/World_War_I\" title=\"World War I\">World War I<\/a> he studied <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Chemical_warfare\" title=\"Chemical warfare\">chemical warfare<\/a> agents, particularly the manufacture of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Phosgene\" title=\"Phosgene\">phosgene<\/a> and the detection of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Mustard_gas\" title=\"Mustard gas\" class=\"mw-redirect\">mustard gas<\/a>. His counterpart on the German side was another Nobel Prize\u2013winning Chemist, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fritz_Haber\" title=\"Fritz Haber\">Fritz Haber<\/a>.<\/p>","name":"Victor Grignard","place_of_birth":"Cherbourg ,  France","place_of_death":"Lyon ,  France","text":"Victor Grignard , Chemistry, 1912","year":1912.0}